    {
      "title": "Subject pronouns (mo, o, ó…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say who does what",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 1,
      "explanation": "The short subject pronouns are mo (I), o (you), ó (he/she/it), a (we), ẹ (you all/polite), wọ́n (they). They sit right before the verb: Mo lọ (I went/go), Ó wá (He came). Yoruba verbs never change form — the pronoun and small particles do all the work.",
      "culture_note": "Ẹ and wọ́n double as respectful singulars — using the plural for an elder is basic politeness.",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Yoruba language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoruba_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} fẹ́ omi.",
          "answer": "Mo",
          "translation": "I want water.",
          "hint": "the 'I' pronoun",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} lọ sí ilé.",
          "answer": "Wọ́n",
          "translation": "They went home.",
          "hint": "the 'they' pronoun",
          "display_order": 2
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} fẹ́ ìwé.",
          "answer": "O",
          "translation": "You want a book.",
          "hint": "you (singular)",
          "display_order": 3
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} lọ sí oko.",
          "answer": "Ó",
          "translation": "He went to the farm.",
          "hint": "he/she — with tone",
          "display_order": 4
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} fẹ́ omi tútù.",
          "answer": "A",
          "translation": "We want cold water.",
          "hint": "we",
          "display_order": 5
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} lọ sí ọjà.",
          "answer": "Ẹ",
          "translation": "You (plural) went to the market.",
          "hint": "you (plural)",
          "display_order": 6
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Tones change meaning",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Hear and write the three tones",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 2,
      "explanation": "Yoruba has three tones: high (á), mid (a, unmarked), low (à) — and they distinguish words: ọkọ́ (hoe), ọkọ (husband), ọkọ̀ (vehicle). Every syllable carries a tone; writing the marks is part of spelling, not decoration.",
      "culture_note": "Talking drums imitate tone patterns — a drummer can 'speak' a proverb because tone carries that much meaning.",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Yoruba language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoruba_language#Grammar"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Tone (linguistics)",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tone_(linguistics)"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Mo ní {{answer}} kan.",
          "answer": "ọkọ̀",
          "translation": "I have a vehicle.",
          "hint": "vehicle — the low-tone twin",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} mi wà ní ilé.",
          "answer": "Ọkọ",
          "translation": "My husband is at home.",
          "hint": "husband — the mid-tone twin",
          "display_order": 2
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Mo fi {{answer}} ra oúnjẹ.",
          "answer": "owó",
          "translation": "I bought food with money.",
          "hint": "money — mid-high tones",
          "display_order": 3
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Fọ {{answer}} rẹ kí o tó jẹun.",
          "answer": "ọwọ́",
          "translation": "Wash your hands before you eat.",
          "hint": "hand — with subdot and high tone",
          "display_order": 4
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ọmọdé dùn.",
          "answer": "Ìgbà",
          "translation": "Childhood days are sweet.",
          "hint": "time/season — low-low tones",
          "display_order": 5
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Mo ra {{answer}} tuntun lánàá.",
          "answer": "ọkọ̀",
          "translation": "I bought a new vehicle yesterday.",
          "hint": "vehicle — the low-tone twin",
          "display_order": 6
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The copulas ni and jẹ́",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what something is",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 3,
      "explanation": "Identity uses ni after the noun phrase: Olùkọ́ ni mí (I am a teacher — lit. teacher is me), Ta ni é? (Who are you?). Jẹ́ states category or profession before the noun: Mo jẹ́ olùkọ́ (I am a teacher). Both are A1 essentials; ni also powers focus later.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Yoruba language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoruba_language#Grammar"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wiktionary: jẹ́ (Yoruba)",
          "url": "https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/j%E1%BA%B9%CC%81#Yoruba"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Mo {{answer}} olùkọ́.",
          "answer": "jẹ́",
          "translation": "I am a teacher.",
          "hint": "the copula for professions and qualities",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Olùkọ́ {{answer}} mí.",
          "answer": "ni",
          "translation": "I am a teacher (it is a teacher that I am).",
          "hint": "the copula for identifying",
          "display_order": 2
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Ó {{answer}} dókítà.",
          "answer": "jẹ́",
          "translation": "She is a doctor.",
          "hint": "the copula for professions and qualities",
          "display_order": 3
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Èmi {{answer}} Adé.",
          "answer": "ni",
          "translation": "I am Ade.",
          "hint": "the copula for identifying",
          "display_order": 4
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Wọ́n {{answer}} àgbẹ̀.",
          "answer": "jẹ́",
          "translation": "They are farmers.",
          "hint": "the copula for professions and qualities",
          "display_order": 5
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Ta {{answer}} ìwọ?",
          "answer": "ni",
          "translation": "Who are you?",
          "hint": "the copula for identifying",
          "display_order": 6
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Location with wà and ní",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say where people and things are",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 4,
      "explanation": "'Be located' is wà, and places take the preposition ní (sí for motion): Ó wà ní ilé (He is at home), Mo wà ní ọjà (I am at the market). With motion verbs: Mo lọ sí ilé-ìwé (I went to school).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
