    {
      "title": "Negation with kò",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what is not so",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 5,
      "explanation": "Kò before the verb negates it: Kò lọ (He didn't go), Mi ò fẹ́ (I don't want — mo becomes mi and kò often shortens to ò after it). Negating wà uses sí: Kò sí ni ilé (He is not at home); 'there isn't' is kò sí.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Yoruba language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoruba_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
